<p>
Fields are the constituent parts of <a href="/docs/Types">types</a>. A field defines a name and a <a href="/docs/Field_Types">field type</a> as well as an optional description and additional parameters. An example <a href="/docs/Text_Field">text field</a> is shown below.
</p>

<pre>
{
	"Name" : "My Text Field",
	"Field Type" : "Text",
	"Description" : "This is an example text field. It stores a minimum of 3 and maximum of 140 characters.",
	"Required" : true,
	"Array" : false,
	"Parameters" : {
		"Minimum Length" : 3,
		"Maximum Length" : 140
	}
}
</pre>

<p>
Fields can specify whether or not they are required by setting the <code>Required</code> key.
</p>

<p>
<a href="/docs/Field_Types">Field types</a> define the type of value that the field accepts. A field with the <a href="/docs/Field_Types">field type</a> <code>Number</code> will only accept numerical values. With the optional additional parameters <code>Minimum</code>, <code>Maximum</code> and <code>Integer</code>, the Field can be restricted to only accepting a range of possible values and can be restricted to whole numbers (integers).
</p>

<p>
Each <a href="/docs/Field_Types">field type</a> has optional parameters appropriate to the type of values it can accept.
</p>

<p>
Fields can also be used to store a collection (array) of values within a single Field by setting the <code>Array</code> key to true. Arrays can be limited to a particular size using the <code>Minimum Array Size</code> and <code>Maximum Array Size</code> keys.
</p>